    en: "NY law keeps a library patron's borrowing, browsing, and other use records confidential. CPLR section 4509 covers public libraries, school libraries, college and university libraries, and special libraries. Records protected include circulation (what was borrowed), computer use, reference desk questions, database searches, interlibrary loan requests, and photocopying. Records cannot be disclosed without the patron's written consent or a court order. A library cannot release records on an administrative request from law enforcement — only judicial subpoenas, court orders, or other statutes mandating disclosure can compel release. The protection exists to keep intellectual freedom intact: people should be able to read and research without worrying about being watched."
